< name>
Lorraine S<//name>
<time>1601995875874<//time><rating>5< /rating>< Review>
I frickin love this place, not just as a Filipina but as a general foodie. The portions here are made for Pinoy dining which means family style. The sinigang, pancit, kare kare, they are all delicious. If you're dining alone, try my favorite all day breakfast items like tapsilog, tocilog, or fish. If you want a fresh taste at Filipino classic dessert, you MUST try halo-halo. My boyfriend and I fight over every morsel and that's kind of the "fun" in this dessert. Every scoop is a surprise.< /Review>

<rate>5</rate><review>I have been craving Lumpia since the place in my town shut down years ago. Friends make it for me here and there but I can never get it when I want it. As kid at one of my friends birthday parties she would also serve Lumpia. It was so good and I've loved it ever since.
I searched for local spots that served Lumpia. Lots came up but only a few in my "backyard ". So we made the drive. The location was easy to find. Parking was easy too. Due to current circumstances they are only serving takeout which was fine for me. The staff was very friendly and helpful with ordering food. The menu has lots of items to choose from.
I came for Lumpia only this trip and it did not dissapoint. I was so elated. I ordered two orders of the pork Lumpia and it was not enough. The Lumpia was cooked just to my liking and the sauce to go with it was a perfect match. When all the Lumpia was gone I was so bummed. Obviously I'm going back it's just a matter of when. Probably sooner than later. I introduced them to my son as well and it was a hit for him</review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPNl6u5f6uMCgTsUcOwpndzCoGwvix80yyzCYit=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPnAS4DIV0R20EAdKZn2siAHhkNdGt02gsMpeAN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>< Response>

< Review>
Food is good, taste like homemade but they give VERY little meat. If you're paying for something with chicken it should have more than a few small pieces of chicken. My noodles had just a few pieces of chicken on top and under was only noodle no meat at all. I could have paid less and gotten vegetable noodles. We were still hungry when we got home. Hopefully they will improve.</Review>

< Text>
This 7 month old Filipino restaurant is patronized not only by Filipinos but by the international community as well.
The food is authentic Filipino and they contribute in promoting Filipino food as a  global brand.
Do not miss the Lechon Kawali- crunchiest deep fried pork belly in liver sauce, the Laing Or taro leaves cooked in coconut milk.
To die for a The ‚ÄúHalo-Halo‚Äù desert topped with purple yam ice cream. I will surely be back for more.  My only suggestion is to have Dinuguan or Pork Blood Stewüôèüèª!!! Kudos to the owners Ted and Trishaüëç</Text>

< username>
Yvy Taesali</username>
</record></dataset><record>
< date>
1566352830142<//date>
<Pics>None< /Pics>< Text>
DELICIOUS!

Growing up in a very large Filipino family, I came in with high expectations and was not let down. On my first(and second) visit I had the pork sisig which they topped with a fried egg and served on a bed of rice and banana leaf. Rich and savory seasoning that brought back some childhood memories. My friend, a white girl whose never had Filipino food beyond Lumpia, had the egg noodle pancit and halo halo; she loved both.

My third visit I had the Lechon(crispy pork belly, pictured). A perfect crispy crust sealed in succulent fatty pork belly.

The restaurant is extremely clean with a contemporary aesthetic and flourishes of Filipino cultural artifacts. Customer service, by whom I assume to be the owners, was excellent every time. I highly recommend for anyone looking to try Filipino cuisine or something different.<//Text>

DISAPPOINTING Service. Will be our last choice for future, though closest to our home.
This was our second visit to the Urgent Care. First time was okay and we had no problems. However, this second  time we experienced bad management service. They took two persons out-of-turn before us even though I  had signed in first. The receptionist is untrained and on top of that is argumentative and not sorry and instead cover up her mistakes.
If such is the level of front facing service, I have to wonder about the experience and quality of medical treatment one would receive in the back.
When we checked in I filled in the requested forms and gave my I'd/insurance card etc. We were told it would take approx 30 minutes of waiting. We were asked if we had been here before and I  told the receptionist that  my wife had been here before and this time it was for me.
Our wait went on for a full hour. During that we witnessed the receptionist arguing with some  couple over their bill. Also, I noticed that they took two persons out of turn. They had signed in after us but were called in before us. When I told the receptionist about that she said that she did not know how the other two and gave no assurance as to when we would have our turn. Instead of being apologetic and trying to  get us in quickly she started to argue with us and blame us and the couple before us for giving her a hard time. They did not make any point to amend anything and thus fell below our expectations. DISAPPOINTING.  Bad service.</text>

I went on a Saturday right as they opened at 9am. I had a severe bladder infection and didn't want to be in a gross Emergency room. <Text>I loved this place, ordered gucamole as an appetizer to enjoy with my drink. Very cool about customizing my drink. Gucamole was HUGE and so flavorable, tasted like homemade chips to go with the dip. Drink was AH-mazing, followed the recipe perfectly. My friend joined me, tasted my drink and ordered the same thing. Very attentive and gracious server, so nice and accommodating. She was a perfect reflection of the restaurant, which was empty at happy hour. People!!! Go to this place and get your Mexican grub on! I moved here a year ago and this is the first place I've eaten those food was so fantastic prepared and plentiful. Very yum. Our meals were so very delicious, I had to order something for my husband. He was so happy when he saw what I brought, both of us are San Diego natives and grew up eating awesome Mexican food. Very happy to find this place!!

My only cons too all these pros? On Google it stated happy hour specials, and this being Taco Tuesday, I was surprised by the lack of specials. Also, even though you got good portions and wonderfully tasty food, it was a bit spendy.

I'd love to see street tacos as an option. I think hiring someone for Cinco de Mayo as an appetizer alternative, charging $1-$2 per taco, would be amazing.

And I'm babbling like a brook. Let me tone it down. I'm coming back for Cinco de Mayo and am bringing a ton of friends, cannot wait to try it again!</Text>< Pictures>

<resp>None<//resp><Text>I loved this place, ordered gucamole as an appetizer to enjoy with my drink. Very cool about customizing my drink. Gucamole was HUGE and so flavorable, tasted like homemade chips to go with the dip. Drink was AH-mazing, followed the recipe perfectly. My friend joined me, tasted my drink and ordered the same thing. Very attentive and gracious server, so nice and accommodating. She was a perfect reflection of the restaurant, which was empty at happy hour. People!!! Go to this place and get your Mexican grub on! I moved here a year ago and this is the first place I've eaten those food was so fantastic prepared and plentiful. Very yum. Our meals were so very delicious, I had to order something for my husband. He was so happy when he saw what I brought, both of us are San Diego natives and grew up eating awesome Mexican food. Very happy to find this place!!

My only cons too all these pros? On Google it stated happy hour specials, and this being Taco Tuesday, I was surprised by the lack of specials. Also, even though you got good portions and wonderfully tasty food, it was a bit spendy.

I'd love to see street tacos as an option. I think hiring someone for Cinco de Mayo as an appetizer alternative, charging $1-$2 per taco, would be amazing.

And I'm babbling like a brook. Let me tone it down. I'm coming back for Cinco de Mayo and am bringing a ton of friends, cannot wait to try it again!< /Text><Date>1553057499375</Date></record></dataset><record>

< review>
Solid OK for Super Pho (from my first experience). Service a little confusing - do I order at the counter or is there table service? Doesn't matter so much for me but other people seemed a little fussy about it.  Went up to the counter to order some veggie pho and non-veggie for the SO. Veggie broth is quite plain but there's plenty of vegetables included as well as sauces to please your palette. SO's large bowl of pho was tasty, just lacking in meat portions. Easy and quick service and parking (street) was not difficult to find on a Sunday evening. Super Pho will satisfy a pho craving for a decent price - as long as you're not a vegetarian ;)</review>

0x80c2ba382acb2b09:0x1d40980439688b81</gmap_id>
<Pics>None<//Pics>< user_name>
David Parker</user_name>
< text>
Small place but serves pretty good pho and is inexpensive.  Tiny indoor seating, might fit about 6 people before it becomes claustrophobic.  They have limited outdoor seating, don't come here if you're a group of 3 or more.  Service is really fast but the parking is really bad.  The last time I went the broth was very salty.  The cashier lady was nice-enough but it's the type of place where none of the workers ever smile.  The food prep / dish-washer guy was wearing a marijuana hat, and it's next door to a seedy looking massage parlor...so go figure.  The overhead speakers was blasting contemporary rap music and various songs from the 90s.  The floor is linoleum, the type you expect to see in a bathroom, and has permanent dirty spots due to years of neglect.  The AC has never worked (to my knowledge).  The lighting inside has a yellow-ish tint, which may give you a headache, but during the day-time it's actually not too bad due to it's large windows and natural lighting. The quality of the food is "good enough."  It does boast self-serve veggie station, which I appreciate, but a lot of the veggies are either wilting or day away from getting thrown out.  The prices though, are fairly decent, costing you less than $9 for a bowl of pho which also "good enough."  As I commented earlier, the soup base has a noticeably salty taste.  They are open late, until around 11pm, sometimes Midnight if it's the weekend.<//text>

<username>Bernard Bentley<//username><time>1427039749887</time><rating>3< /rating>< review>
After heading to Phorage and not being getting my pho craving satisfied, I decided to check this place out. It's a smaller place than Phorage, but the food was decent. They have one high chair for the place and you order your dish up front. It's definitely cheaper than Phorage and I felt there were more noodles in the bowl. I especially liked the all you can add condiments. I love onions and basil so I was excited to learn that I could add as much as I wanted to! I even got an extra helping of noodles! Looking forward to going back.

3 stars because I noticed that some of the condiments weren't very fresh.< /review>

<review>Dont know why this place has any good reviews! I got teriyaki shrimp and the shrimp were VERY overcooked, rubbery, and smelled so fishy. They were definitely cooked with no seasoning, boiled I think, and then teriyaki sauce was sprinkled over, but it didnt leave any flavor on them. They tasted like they weren't cleaned at all and had been marinating in their own, old fishy juices for days and were on the verge of going bad, but were cooked anyway!(I ate one before I realized how bad they were) They were not deveined completely, still having pieces of poop in them! Then, as a side, you get a bunch of bagged salad and cheap rice with very little meat for the price. I dont go for teriyaki to have bagged salad with italian or ranch dressing! I go for the terryaki! My boyfriend got a burger which was equally crappy. Dont recommend anyone to eat here.<//review>< gmapID>

< review>
In a world where most purchases are made "on-line" (and largely "sight-unseen"), Paul's Photo is almost UNIQUE.  If you have photographic "questions", or are seeking GUIDANCE,  Paul's is a place where you can talk to real people who are knowledgeable, and enthusiastic about photography. Plus, I find their prices to be competitive with any you can find; either on-line, or the "New York super-stores". Carlos Flores<//username>
< review>
This is my second visit, and the food gets better every time. Food is fresh, savory and well woth the price. You won't find a similar place in the vicinity to rival this location. I live in the valley, the drive is well worth it. Today my daughter and I had the chicken and lamb pita, respectively. Both were delicious and filled with goodness. The pita bread is soft and consistent, it won't break apart, and meat portions are substantial, to say one was enough to fill me. Their gr fries are off the hook!  one person can eat two orders, easily. Plenty of parking on the back of the building. I look forward to my next visit.<//review>

< review>
This place is really good! I had a pork wrap but I should have gotten a salad since I also ordered hummus and pita, which is freshly made and extremely delicious. The serving of the pita came with Greek fries, shoe string fries, nicely seasoned. The presentation of both the items I got, the hummus with pita bread and the pork pita was elegant and I didn't want to eat it because it was pretty. The food was delicious as well. I also got freshly made cucumber lemonade, yum, so refreshing! Definitely coming back to try different items from the menu. The establishment is really clean and they have gender neutral restrooms (2). The entrance is from the parking lot but you can see the restaurant from the main street. Definitely will came back, fresh ingredients and clean establishment.< /review>

<user>105012813294540788881<//user><Pics>None</Pics>< Text>
Been wanting to try this place for a while since we can't get back to Greece this year.
The gyro is pretty good, not authentic, but pretty good (has pickled onions slices in it??). The Avgolemono is a hard pass, as is the Bougatsa. The avgolemono is very watery, salty, and unlike any avgolemono I've ever had (it has chives in it??). The bougatsa cream is lacking in flavor and kinda doughy.
Their frappes are pretty legit though, and use Greek frappe granules to make them.
It's very hard to find authentic Greek food on the west coast, and we had high hopes driving from San Diego. The hunt continues.<//Text>

<Review>Affordable and very delicious. I had the merida plate with thinly sliced lamb which included salad, rice, fries as topping, and one side of choice. I loved the additional side of choice option because most Mediterranean places the sides are fixed. I chose tzatziki because I love large quantities of it. The salad was unique; overall the plate was delicious and reasonably priced under $15. I also ordered a side of halloumi (not pictured) which was amazing ($7 for four slices and pita). Great customer service. Cashier was helpful with suggestions and the food runner always checked in to make sure everything was ok. < Text>
Walked in with no appointment and was immediately greeted and welcomed in for a haircut, Ky is a very nice lady! But I feel the price of $40 to get my hair thinned and cleaned up (styled instead of men‚Äôs haircut price) is too much. It only took her no more then 10 minutes and it felt rushed because a customer with an appointment walked in and was waiting at the counter. That being said, even though I didn't like the price I still paid it because it was agreed upon before hand and I thought there was going to be a lot more done then what was. BUT I could've gotten the same experience at RMH in the mall for $25. Ky a word of advice, the best businesses adjust there prices to compete with the competition. I understand you charge how you do because you feel it is what you are worth. But the majority of your bad reviews have to do with the price being too high. If that's a common theme then its probably true compared to your competition. If you really care about your customer experience and about the online reviews then you would listen to what is being said and adjust accordingly. If your prices go down, I will definitely come back! I will say I do love my new haircut :)</Text>

<Text>I went to Ky's hair design salon back in December 2014 to get my hair colored. I have black hair, and wanted a golden blonde color. After i told her and showed her lots of pictures of what i wanted, she expressed confidence that she could do it. She kept priding about herself and that she has done this for years. I only did the top half of my hair. Basically had chunky blonde highlights added. While this was happening, she had some men walk in for hair cuts. She had them wait while she finished coloring my hair because she was the only worker. I had felt like she rushed to finish me so she could do her walk-ins. When she finished with the highlights i had expected her to put a hair cap on me, but instead she put a plastic walmart bag on my head. Which i thought was really strange. While i waited under the heater for my hair, she cut about 2 mens hair. After her salon was empty, she returned to me to wash my hair. I also had a deep condition. Halfway thru blow drying my hair, she turned off the blow dryer and said we were done (note that there was more walk-ins waiting for hair cuts). When I went to the counter to pay her, i asked what kind of payment she accepted. She then said, "oh u don't have cash?". I did have enough cash on me, but i just wanted to ask if she accepts credit/debit. I ended up paying in cash and left with my hair damp. I was confused if my hair was supposed to be damped and for it to air dry the rest due to the deep condition? Still don't know, but i felt like she was just rushing so she could get to her walk-in customers and don't lose money from them because she did have to send off 1 customer. When I got home and dried my hair, i was not pleased with the outcome. Being the shy person that i am, i called another hair salon to try and make my hair look nicer. They had asked me to go back to Ky because she did the work so she should be the one to fix it. So I called her regarding not being pleased with the outcome and i set up another appointment to go in. At my 2nd visit, i told her that the outcome of my hair just didn't look good, so she recommended i highlight the bottom half of my hair to match the top. So i agreed. She did not end up giving me any discount and just charged me full price.

Overall, if u just want a simple haircut i think she can get the job done. If u want colored hair, as much as she prides herself in her work, she can't walk the talk as the results did not show. She did not make me feel important and top priority (being her ONLY scheduled appointment for the day).

<Name>Jason Nash< /Name><Date>1562573341386< /Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
<Text>"Nice picture, Jason.  A demolished piece of pie?  Really?"

Yeah.  Meant to take more and better photos, but after a fun day swimming at the North Fork of the American River, we were hungry, and I was only reminded to take pictures at this point.

In a way this is very representative of Ikeda's.  The food is so good, it will be gone before you know it.

Pictured is a slice (mostly) of Triple Berry Pie.  Almost as excellent as either of their Razzleberry options (cobbler or pie, both magnificent).

You have to try the Marionberry shake.  And then everyone you know must try it.

Other musts:

*Truffle Parmesan Fries.  Holy heck.

*Ikeda's Gourmet Wagyu Burger.  Be hungry

*the Patty Melt.  No, really, the Patty Melt.

*Finally, the Teriyaki burger has no pineapple, but uses caramelized onions instead.  It's so sweet and tasty that I probably had it three times before I realized it.

This is one of my must-stops returning to Reno from any California trip.

Did I mention the farm fresh produce and collection of homemade sauces?

There are so many reasons to love Ikeda's.

Last but not least:  they are 45 seconds off the freeway (60 if you're stuck at the light), and have plenty of parking.< /Text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNgCGy1AdeGzV6HSVAcauao9rSBwDfLrTPClv4X=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics>< Response>

< date>
1566164080641< /date>
<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Fun little market.  Definitely a go to if you're in the area.  I would suggest between 11 and. 1130 for lunch.  By noon it was packed,  no parking and a never ending line for food and checkout at the store. I would suggest sharing a double patty burger because they were thin patties with big buns, better meat to bread ratio.  The apple pie was good, but a little sugar and cinnamon on the crust would've made it delicious.  I wasn't sure about going with all the reviews,  but overall a great experience.  The knocked out the orders really fast and everyone had a great attitude.</Review>

<Review>I love stopping here for lunch after coming over the pass from Reno. Excellent burgers, huge delicious pies and friendly service. They also have a small store filled with produce, baked goods, etc. I picked up some peach muffins for the next day's breakfast, they had big chunks of fresh peach in them - - I don't know if I've had a better muffin. It does get busy around lunchtime so plan accordingly. Also they have the Impossible Burger here... I was pleasantly surprised at how well it passed for real meat.< /Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOD5WQMbAYHaVNoSKVwwTTjWZKWdWrpKG4t3jDN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures><rating>5< /rating><Resp>None</Resp><UserId.>101454896227491402850</UserId.>< username>

</dataset><record>
< Rating>
2<//Rating>
< response>
None</response>
< username>
Scott Smith</username>
< text>
I'm a big fan of family owned shops, but not when they aren't taking care of their own store or investing any money into it.  I have seen the Ikeda market for decades growing up in the area but had never stopped in, so I decided to finally see for myself today.  The restaurant side of the building was old and filthy, there was food in the blinds, flies all around, and worn out tables and chairs that looked 30 years old.  The food was decent, but overpriced ($15 for a burger and fries).  Walked through the market section afterwards, it was nicer and gave off a farmers market vibe, but still pricey.  You can tell the fruits and veggies come from outside suppliers and the "specialty" jams, jellies, and other items are mass produced.  This place has been open long enough and has enough traffic that the Ikeda family should really have invested more money in fixing up their place or pricing goods for better value.  Overall it was a disappointment to me.<//text>

Still my fave after 20 years of going up and down this highway.

Today, we shared two amazing chicken and steak pot pies with our kids and purchased fresh nectarines for our vacation home.

Thanks for evolving, Ikeda's! We weren't in the mood for burgers but craved a hot meal. Pies hit the spot and kids didn't complain one bit.

< Name>
Jeff Kwong<//Name>
<time>1534191928990</time>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Review>
Stopped by Ikeda's after a round of golf in Auburn.  What a great decision.  It was very busy and parking was a challenge, but I think this is related to everyone returning from Tahoe on a Sunday.  We stopped by for lunch as well as to pick up some fruit and pies.

Lunch rating: 4/5
Fruit ratings: 5/5
Pie Rating: 5+/5 ... probably the best apple pie I've had in the Sac area (far better than apple hill).

The teriyaki burger was good, the fries were good, but I couldn't get over how many flies there were (probably unavoidable as a fruit stand), but I didn't know what to expect.  I wouldn't classify the place as dirty though.  It was clean.  The staff was friendly and the owner said Hi.  The peaches I bought were amazing, and again the apple pie was simply the best.  Glad to have found Ikeda's.< /Review>

<UserId.>101048609281037389431</UserId.>< review>
We stop at Ikedas every time we head to Lake Tahoe every August. The annual pie is something to look forward to sharing as a family. This year was a huge disappointment! We purchased a $20 peach cobbler and it was like a pie crust filled with gelatin. It tasted bland, there may have been two peaches in the entire pie. It was like a peach jello with no flavor. The crumbles on top were a disappointing few. We felt really ripped off. Maybe you are hurting for a profit and decided to cut back of ingredients but you lost this family.</review>

<Time>1527027630183</Time><user_name>Brian McSteen<//user_name>< review>
Of all the places you could stop on your way back West from Tahoe, this is one of the best. The burgers and pot pie are so good ‚Äì not health for you, but tasty. The most recent visit I had the chicken pot pie, which felt like a great bang for my buck. The pot pie was massive and very filling for $8. If you're able, I would avoid the vegetarian options here. They are frozen, not farm fresh like their other ingredients. Also, get at least a slice of pie and walk around the shop adjacent to the fast food mart! It's a very relaxing farm stand with great produce from the surrounding agricultural area.<//review>

0x809b056a04c55c77:0xb242bebb67a4ca5b< /GmapID>
< Review>
Someone told me they had the best burgers in town here so I decided to try it out. Then I remembered seeing Ikeda's on TV and decided I wanted to try it. I have mixed feelings about it.
I tried the Gourmet Wagyu Burger since it came with grass fed beef. It was a truly wonderful burger. Not sure what I was tasting that was so good, maybe the hint of truffle or maybe the cheese. I would have preferred they keep that mountain of fries and trim $2 off the hefty price tag, and 2 pounds of fat.
Wash your hands before you get there. You will lose your appetite when you walk past all the rotting food on the way back to the restrooms. Totally unacceptable. Many of the items in the store are not priced. I could not find anyone to ask, and I wasn't about to wait in line to get a surprise at the checkstand.</Review>

<name>Zack Vestal< /name><user_id>101443997435401961531< /user_id>< time>
1563770595983< /time>
< GmapID>
0x809b056a04c55c77:0xb242bebb67a4ca5b<//GmapID>
< Resp>
None</Resp>
< Text>
I was taken to this restaurant by a friend of mine!  This friend of mine was excited to eat here as we were passing though town!  We arrived at dinner time and proceeded to order our food!  The menu is easy to understand and order from (being from cowboy country in Nevada i was not in anyway interested in the hipster/vegan options but what can you expect in California?)! I ordered the double buger with cheese,  regular fries,  drink,  and a slice of apple pie!!  My complete order came to about $21 (((((whoah))))) maybe it will be worth it once i taste it!! I had ticket number 98 and they were serving people with ticket number of 70-75, so i would be in for a long wait, but its ok,  i will just get some Dr Pepper  and chill. The Dr Pepper ended up being mostly soda water and pretty nasty, just enough to not feel like complaining but gross enough to not enjoy it!  Ended up not chilling though,  the air conditioning was obviously not working,  it was hotter inside then outside!!  Miserable!!!!!  However the grocery store section was perfectly fine and cold!! Finally after 30-40 mins my order was ready! First thing, the fries were just at that point where they were warm enough to be edible but a minute later they were cold soggy fries, only edible dipped in ketchup (if your fries cant be eaten by themselves with no seasoning or sauses,  are they really that good?)!  They were at least home made looking?!  Now the burger?  The patties were miniscule at best and dry to the squeeze,  no juices flowing from them!  They were super thin and cooked pass well done!  The cheese and condiments were good, but the meat is what makes a good burger,  i remember back in my childhood my dad cooking burgers as thick as chicken breast!!! So unless the meat is cooked to satisfaction, what is the point of eating it? The dutch apple pie had tons of flavor and seemed like it was made with tasty apples!  I am not sure about "Dutch Apple Pie", but i am pretty sure that the bottom crust should be cooked solid and be flacky not just raw dough!!

So once again I think I have found one of those restaurants that is cool and hip to go to, (like IN n Out)  so thats the only reason they are open,  not because they serve us great food all the time!  Hopefully this was just a bad day for them?  I will give any restaurant a second chance, and i will do the same here!!

Happy Eating!!!!</Text>
</record></dataset><record>

<user_name>Zack Vestal<//user_name>< gmapID>
0x809b056a04c55c77:0xb242bebb67a4ca5b< /gmapID>
<Text>I was taken to this restaurant by a friend of mine!  This friend of mine was excited to eat here as we were passing though town!  We arrived at dinner time and proceeded to order our food!  The menu is easy to understand and order from (being from cowboy country in Nevada i was not in anyway interested in the hipster/vegan options but what can you expect in California?)! I ordered the double buger with cheese,  regular fries,  drink,  and a slice of apple pie!!  My complete order came to about $21 (((((whoah))))) maybe it will be worth it once i taste it!! I had ticket number 98 and they were serving people with ticket number of 70-75, so i would be in for a long wait, but its ok,  i will just get some Dr Pepper  and chill. The Dr Pepper ended up being mostly soda water and pretty nasty, just enough to not feel like complaining but gross enough to not enjoy it!  Ended up not chilling though,  the air conditioning was obviously not working,  it was hotter inside then outside!!  Miserable!!!!!  However the grocery store section was perfectly fine and cold!! Finally after 30-40 mins my order was ready! First thing, the fries were just at that point where they were warm enough to be edible but a minute later they were cold soggy fries, only edible dipped in ketchup (if your fries cant be eaten by themselves with no seasoning or sauses,  are they really that good?)!  They were at least home made looking?!  Now the burger?  The patties were miniscule at best and dry to the squeeze,  no juices flowing from them!  They were super thin and cooked pass well done!  The cheese and condiments were good, but the meat is what makes a good burger,  i remember back in my childhood my dad cooking burgers as thick as chicken breast!!! So unless the meat is cooked to satisfaction, what is the point of eating it? The dutch apple pie had tons of flavor and seemed like it was made with tasty apples!  I am not sure about "Dutch Apple Pie", but i am pretty sure that the bottom crust should be cooked solid and be flacky not just raw dough!!

So once again I think I have found one of those restaurants that is cool and hip to go to, (like IN n Out)  so thats the only reason they are open,  not because they serve us great food all the time!  Hopefully this was just a bad day for them?  I will give any restaurant a second chance, and i will do the same here!!

Happy Eating!!!!</Text>< Response>

<user_id>108833816486311466401<//user_id><user_name>autumnpumpkin T.</user_name>< date>
1503086795783<//date>
< Rate>
3<//Rate>
<text>Great place to stop by! Friendly staff and great customer service! The pies are a little expensive, but good. Some are extremely sweet since either used with canned or real fruit or half. Sometimes the pies have seeds or stem in them-depending on if they were used with real or canned fruit. Good pie choices! Recommend the Peach "Cobbler" though its technically not a Cobbler but a pie. Variety of Fries-would not recommend the small/thin fries since they are overcooked. The freezes inside can be refreshing on a hot day. Yet they are very icy and I mostly get balls of ice in the cups-but once in a while its nice.
The food varies on preparation time. 5-15min. The Salmon sandwich is good-would recommend it, however they did down size the amount of salmon on it by shredding it into small pieces to make it appear as a lot. Also reduced the veggies on it-I had a sliver of pepper and wasn't really happy with that-and a little too oily-even though the sub tasted pretty good. The ranch has added water to it so they can give out more.

There is an outdoor seating area as well as inside. I do love sitting outside!
Would recommend that they have a sign regarding have your dog on a leash, so people can be conscientious of others and for their own  dog's safety of running in the street.<//text><pics>None</pics>< resp>
None</resp>

<rating>1<//rating>< Text>
There was a significant number if flies inside the burger shack. I get that people come in and out of the door and flies will inevitably get in. However, they have blowers which could help mitigate this and would recommend investing in these.

Personally, the flies were disgusting. After seeing flies crawling on the tip of the mayonnaise dispenser (on the actual business end of the dispenser where the Mayo comes out), I skipped the Mayo. I grabbed a little ketchup and as I was spreading the kethup on my bun, one of the flies landed on my burger. At this point I said f#$& it and threw my burger out and left. Flies crawl around on all sorts of disgusting stuff. If I can see them crawling around on patrons food, I can only imagine what a horror show it is in the kitchen< /Text>

< Text>
Ikeda's is a traditional stop for those traveling East or West between Reno and Sacramento. It offers  a cafe and grocery featuring produce  grown by local farmers. It's also famous for baked goods including freshly baked fruit pies and cobblers. Ikeda's produces condiments and dressings including its family recipe teriyaki sauce. The selection is great, but beware: The prices are not for the faint of heart or a thin wallet. Pies cost nearly 20 bucks. Not bad for an annual stop, but be ready for sticker shock.<//Text>

< review>
Overall, I would not eat her again for a couple of reasons. We ordered a bacon cheese burger with fries and a shake but ended up getting a veggie burger instead. This was not a problem as they quickly fix the issue and prepared us a burger however the burger tasted really weird like it had some sort of cinnamon Spice in it. There was also what I consider to be somewhat of a health problem, I asked if they had ranch when the girl was ringing this up and she pointed to some ranch on the counter. There were several little plastic tubs of ranch inside of a big plastic Square tub that weren't refrigerated. Of course I was sketchy on this because it was Dairy but I did go over and pick one of them up to at least see if it was cold, it was not. I would not want to risk eating a hamburger or anything else that is being prepared by people that do not understand the basics of chilling food such as dairy. It is also very pricey, it was $15 for a shake fries and a burger, thank God we split it especially since I didn't eat my half and left it on the table.</review>

< review>
I went there earlier today on my way home back to NV.  I had their garden burger, which the base consisted of rice, and it was delicious.  It was very tasty, and being vegetarian, I absolutely love that they have alternatives, including tofu burger.  The fries are delicious and most definitely fresh, rather than frozen fake-fries, as my ex would say.  Upon checking out their menu, I saw that they have several different flavors of milkshakes, all of which contain real fruit.  I opted to try the banana milkshake, and it was the most delicious milkshake I've ever tasted.  Next time, I plan on trying their marionberry milkshake, as that sounds delicious.  They are always crowded, and it's for a good reason.  Ikeda's truly is amazing.<//review>

It is a nice but expensive place with lots of organic products. We bought a pie, a sushi bowl, and burger. Found the pies and burger disappointing especially for the price but the bowl and fries were pretty good. Not terrible but honestly wouldn't go out of my way to shop or eat there considering the price and taste of the food. The staff is very friendly and helpful and this review is in no-way meant to be negative towards them.</Text>
